'''Maria Weizmann''' ({{lang-ru|Мари́я Ве́йцман}}; born 1893) was a sister of Israeli politician and scientist [[Chaim Weizmann]] (the first President of the State of [[Israel]]). She graduated from a university in [[Switzerland]] and worked as a doctor in [[Moscow]] from 1915.
Maria Weizman and her husband V.M. Savitsky were long denied the right to emigrate from the [[Soviet Union]] by the authorities (see also [[Refusenik (Soviet Union)|refusenik]]). Her husband was arrested in 1949.
On February 10, 1953 she was arrested in connection with the alleged [[Doctors' plot]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.il/books?id=V-ZVcsl0h3EC&pg=PA463|title=Encyclopedia of Cold War Espionage, Spies, and Secret Operations|last=Trahair|first=R. C. S.|last2=Miller|first2=Robert Lawrence|date=2013-10-18|publisher=Enigma Books|isbn=9781936274260|language=en}}</ref> Her case was handled by the [[GRU]] (as opposed to [[MGB (USSR)|MGB]] as it was common), an evidence of its importance to the Soviet regime. After [[Joseph Stalin]]'s death and the admission by the Soviet leadership that the "plot" was made up, she was still kept in [[Lubyanka (KGB)|Lubyanka]] prison, and released only on August 12, 1953. Weizmann immigrated to Israel in 1956.
She was officially rehabilitated after [[Perestroika]] in 1989.
